This paper explores the effects of skip connections in stacked bidirectional LSTMs for sequential tagging, which is a common task in natural language processing. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also presents experiments using deep learning techniques, which are commonly studied in sub-categories such as cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of gated identity functions, which are commonly used in neural networks for tasks such as image recognition, which falls under the sub-category cs.CV (Computer Vision). Finally, the paper discusses the performance of the proposed method, which is related to optimization techniques, which are studied in sub-category cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
